4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, individuals and entities are
6 entitled to enter into various types of agreements that
7 prohibit a party to the agreement or another individual
8 or entity from discussing or disclosing certain
9 information.
10 This bill would render unenforceable any
11 provision of an agreement that prohibits an individual
12 or entity from disclosing certain acts of sexual abuse
13 or facts related to certain acts of sexual abuse.
14
15
16 A BILL
17 TO BE ENTITLED
18 AN ACT
19
20 Relating to civil procedure; to render unenforceable
21 any provision of an agreement that prohibits an individual or
22 entity from disclosing certain acts of sexual abuse or facts
23 related to certain acts of sexual abuse.
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
25 Section 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as
26 Trey's Law.
27 Section 2. The Legislature finds and declares all of
28 the following:
Page 1

the following:
HB93 INTRODUCED
29 (1) Sexual abuse causes significant and lasting harm to
30 individuals and society as a whole.
31 (2) Sexual abuse survivors often experience long-term
32 physical, psychological, and emotional trauma.
33 (3) The State of Alabama has a compelling interest in
34 preventing sexual abuse, supporting victims, and ensuring that
35 the law does not shield perpetrators or impede public safety.
36 (4) Any agreement that prohibits an individual or
37 entity from disclosing an act of sexual abuse or facts related
38 to an act of sexual abuse is against the public policy of this
39 state.
40 (5) This act is intended to protect survivors' rights
41 to speak freely and to maintain privacy and confidentiality
42 regarding their identities, experiences, and trauma.
43 Section 3. (a) For the purposes of this section, the
44 term "sexual abuse" means any conduct that would constitute a
45 criminal violation of Articles 4, 4A, 4B, 6, 6A, 8, or 11 of
46 Chapter 6 of Title 13A, Code of Alabama 1975, or any of the
47 offenses listed in Section 15-20A-5, Code of Alabama 1975,
48 regardless of whether the conduct has led to a criminal
49 charge, conviction, adjudication, or sentence.
50 (b)(1) Any provision of a nondisclosure agreement,
51 confidentiality agreement, employment agreement, settlement
52 agreement, or any other type of agreement that prohibits an
53 individual or entity from disclosing an act of sexual abuse or
54 facts related to an act of sexual abuse to another individual
55 or entity is void and unenforceable.
56 (2) This subsection shall apply to any agreement
Page 2

(2) This subsection shall apply to any agreement
HB93 INTRODUCED
57 entered into, executed, or amended on or after October 1,
58 2026, and shall apply solely to elements of an agreement
59 related to the act of sexual abuse and shall not apply to
60 other aspects of an agreement, including, but not limited to,
61 compensation.
62 Section 4. This act shall become effective on October
63 1, 2026.
